\i\fs44 \cf0 Listen, there\'92s nothing wrong with sour cream out of a tub, but man can that stuff ever be thick.\'a0 That\'92s why I love crema \'97 the rich, delicately sour, slightly thickened cream used in Mexican cooking.\'a0 I like to think of it as a thinner version of cr\'e8me fra\'eeche. Unlike sour cream, crema Mexicana won\'92t break or separate when heated, making it ideal for stirring into warm sauces.\'a0 Sure there are a few good brands out there, but making it yourself at home couldn\'92t be any simpler.\'a0 All you need is some heavy cream, a cultured dairy product like buttermilk or yogurt and some culinary caj\'f3nes.\'a0 That\'92s right, in order to get this stuff to the right consistency you\'92re gonna have to leave it out on your counter overnight\'85unrefrigerated.\'a0 But don\'92t worry, considering the resilience of the ultra-pasteurized heavy whipping cream sold in most supermarkets, it\'92s gonna take a lot more than a night on your counter to spoil.\'a0 I too was a bit worried the first time I made it, but trust me, this recipe works like a charm.\'a0 The finished crema is complex, nutty and has a beautiful pourable texture, perfect for spooning on tacos, enchiladas or even a simple baked potato.\'a0 Or, do what I do and drizzle it on a plate of loaded, cheesy nachos \'97 it certainly beats a thick glob of cold sour cream.\cf2 \
